 <Header id="D">
  <h1>Using Command Line Arguments</h1>
 </Header><div>
  <p class="firstLine">
   To use command line arguments in your code, modify the signature of <tt
    >main()</tt
   >
   by adding two additional parameter variables: an integer (typically named <tt
    >argc</tt
   >), and an array of C-strings of type <tt>char*</tt>, typically named <tt
    >argv</tt
   >.
  </p>
  <pre
   class="language-cpp"><code>int main(int argc, char *argv[])
&lbrace;
    // your code here
&rbrace;</code></pre>
  <p>
   The first parameter, (<tt>argc</tt>), is the <mark>number of elements</mark> in
   the command-line array. The second, (<tt>argv</tt>), is an array of <tt
    >char*</tt
   >, because each argument is passed as a character array or C-style string.
  </p>
  <p>
   The first element, <tt>argv[0]</tt> is the name of the program,
   <mark>as invoked on the command line</mark>. A common error is to grab <tt
    >argv[0]</tt
   > when you really wanted the first argument, which is <tt>argv[1]</tt>. You
   need not use the names
   <tt>argc</tt> and <tt>argv</tt>, but it may confuse people if you donâ€™t.
  </p>
 </div>
</Layout>
